Implement the public `filename/1` function.

It takes a binary `input` and produces a filesystem-safe filename, returning
`{:ok, sanitized}` on success or `{:error, :empty}` when nothing usable
remains. The transformation must be applied in order:

1. Strip null bytes (`\0`).
2. Strip path separators — both `/` and `\` — so traversal sequences like
   `../../etc/passwd` lose their slashes (leaving dot runs to be neutralised
   below).
3. Keep only the safe character set: alphanumerics, underscores (`_`),
   hyphens (`-`), and dots (`.`). Every other character is removed.
4. Collapse any run of two or more consecutive dots into a single dot. This
   handles both traversal remnants (e.g. `....etcpasswd` → `.etcpasswd`) and
   double-dot typos (e.g. `hello..world` → `hello.world`).
5. Strip any leading or trailing dots left over after the collapse
   (e.g. `.etcpasswd` → `etcpasswd`).

If the resulting string is empty, return `{:error, :empty}`; otherwise return
`{:ok, sanitized}`.

